Task 1: Decompile APK with APKTool
Step 1.1: Setup Working Environment
Create organized directories for the analysis workflow:

# Create directory structure
mkdir -p ~/apk-analysis/{apk-files,decompiled-output,jadx-output,reports}
cd ~/apk-analysis

# Verify APKTool installation
apktool --version
Step 1.2: Download Sample APK
Download a vulnerable Android application for analysis:

# Download DIVA (Damn Insecure and Vulnerable App)
cd ~/apk-analysis/apk-files
wget https://github.com/payatu/diva-android/raw/master/diva-beta.apk

# Verify download
ls -lh diva-beta.apk
file diva-beta.apk
Step 1.3: Extract APK Information
Gather basic metadata before decompilation:

# Extract APK metadata
aapt dump badging diva-beta.apk | grep -E "package|application-label|sdkVersion"

# View APK structure
unzip -l diva-beta.apk | head -20
Step 1.4: Decompile with APKTool
Use APKTool to extract resources and Smali code:

# Decompile APK
cd ~/apk-analysis/decompiled-output
apktool d ../apk-files/diva-beta.apk -o diva-decompiled

# Explore structure
cd diva-decompiled
tree -L 2
Step 1.5: Analyze AndroidManifest.xml
Examine the manifest for security configurations:

# View manifest
cat AndroidManifest.xml

# Extract permissions
grep "uses-permission" AndroidManifest.xml

# Find exported components
grep -E "exported.*true" AndroidManifest.xml

# Check debug flag
grep "debuggable" AndroidManifest.xml
Key Analysis Points:

Dangerous permissions (STORAGE, LOCATION, CAMERA)
Exported activities/services without proper protection
Debug flag enabled in production builds
Backup settings and network security configuration
Task 2: Analyze Code with JADX
Step 2.1: Decompile to Java Source
Convert DEX bytecode to readable Java code:

# Create JADX output directory
cd ~/apk-analysis/jadx-output

# Decompile with JADX
jadx -d jadx-diva-output ~/apk-analysis/apk-files/diva-beta.apk

# Verify output
ls -la jadx-diva-output/
tree jadx-diva-output/sources -L 3
Step 2.2: Navigate Source Code
Explore the decompiled Java source structure:

# Navigate to sources
cd jadx-diva-output/sources

# Find main package
find . -name "*.java" | head -10

# List activity files
find . -name "*Activity*.java"
Step 2.3: Search for Security Issues
Use grep to identify common vulnerabilities:

# Search for hardcoded credentials
grep -rn -i "password\s*=\|secret\s*=\|key\s*=" . --include="*.java"

# Find SQL operations (potential injection)
grep -rn "SELECT\|INSERT\|UPDATE\|DELETE" . --include="*.java" | grep "+"

# Locate file operations
grep -rn "openFileOutput\|getSharedPreferences" . --include="*.java"

# Find network operations
grep -rn "http://\|HttpURLConnection" . --include="*.java"

# Check for weak crypto
grep -rn "DES\|MD5\|SHA1" . --include="*.java"
Step 2.4: Analyze Specific Vulnerabilities
Examine MainActivity and other critical files:

# View MainActivity
find . -name "MainActivity.java" -exec cat {} \;

# Search for insecure storage
grep -rn "MODE_WORLD_READABLE\|MODE_WORLD_WRITABLE" . --include="*.java"

# Find WebView configurations
grep -rn "setJavaScriptEnabled\|addJavascriptInterface" . --include="*.java"
